04085nam a22005775i 9780822394686DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20112011ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223946867 a10.1515/97808223946862doi  a(DE-B1597)553551  a(OCoLC)1140359991  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aGE199.C6bC46 2011 7aLIT0060002bisacsh04a333.72095125/090492221 aBeverley, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLatinamericanism after 9/11 /cJohn Beverley. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (176 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPost-Contemporary Interventions00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Latinamericanism after 9/11 -- t2. The Persistence of the Nation (against Empire) -- t3. Deconstruction and Latinamericanism (apropos Alberto Moreiras's The Exhaustion of Difference) -- t4. Between Ariel and Caliban: The Politics of Location of Latinamericanism and the Question of Solidarity -- t5. The Neoconservative Turn -- t6. Beyond the Paradigm of Disillusion: Rethinking the Armed Struggle in Latin America -- t7. The Subaltern and the State -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Latinamericanism after 9/11, John Beverley explores Latinamericanist cultural theory in relation to new modes of political mobilization in Latin America. He contends that after 9/11, the hegemony of the United States and the neoliberal assumptions of the so-called Washington Consensus began to fade in Latin America. At the same time, the emergence in Latin America of new leftist governments-the marea rosada or "pink tide"-gathered momentum. Whatever its outcome, the marea rosada has shifted the grounds of Latinamericanist thinking in a significant way. Beverley proposes new paradigms better suited to Latin America's reconfigured political landscape. In the process, he takes up matters such as Latin American postcolonial and cultural studies, the relation of deconstruction and Latinamericanism, the persistence of the national question and cultural nationalism in Latin America, the neoconservative turn in recent Latin American literary and cultural criticism, and the relation between subalternity and the state. Beverley's perspective flows out of his involvement with the project of Latin American subaltern studies, but it also defines a position that is in some ways postsubalternist. He takes particular issue with recent calls for a "posthegemonic" politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aEnvironmental protectionxSocial aspectszChinazHong Kong. 0aEnvironmentalismzChinazHong Kong. 0aEthnologyzChinazHong Kong. 0aPolitical participationzChinazHong Kong. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822394686zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822394686423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822394686.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles